DC  L-serine degradation
DR  MetaCyc; SERDEG-PWY;
CC  The L-serine degradation pathway consists of a single enzymatic reaction,
CC  catalyzed by EC 4.3.1.17, L-serine ammonia-lyase. The enzyme, which is
CC  pyridoxal 5'-phosphate-dependent, dehydrates L-serine to the enamine
CC  intermediate 2-aminoprop-2-enoate. This intermediate is very unstable. It
CC  tautomerizes immediately and spontaneously to the imine form
CC  2-iminopropanoate, which is then non-enzymatically hydrolyzed to form
CC  pyruvate and free ammonium [1].
